pr_review_comment_body:
I think the revocation packet is on a different UID, at the very end:

{{{
rev:::1:C0A2586F09D77C82:1471422777::::heartsucker <heartsucker@autistici.org>:28x:::::10:
}}}

But I still don't understand why one would reset curuid…

@kevincvlam 
There is definitely a tradeoff here between extensibility and type-safety/readability of the api. 

The simplest api would be to let user's write their pod as a nested dict that gets directly translated into kubernetes json, but that can be painful for some tasks.

yep in the brave code, looks similar, too, except it uses two signals: shared (ex I didn't start a new trace from an incoming request) and "sr"

```java
    // don't report server-side timestamp on shared or incomplete spans
    if (shared && (flags & FLAG_SR) != 0) {
      span.timestamp(null).duration(null);
    }
```

Bah, I missed the fact it's inside a closure. Same thing apply there though:
```go
func(in interface{}, pa...
var (
        v interface{}
        err error
)
```

It does work. For example, this query returned [one hit](http://localhost:5000/api/literature/1498589)
```
{
   "query": {
      "bool": {
          "should": [
              {
                "term": {
                    "earliest_date": "2016-11-16"
                }
              },
              {
                 "term": {
                    "preprint_date": "2016-11-16"
                }
              }
          ]
      }
   }
}
```.

I also tried with `earliest_date` and `legacy_creation_date` whose value was different than `2016-11-16` and still got the same, correct hit.

@vighneshbirodkar 
@stefanv 
So, I guess our main priority now is to get first prototype faster
and then when it works, we can speed it with Cython.

I suggest that for now I will focus on the implementing the evaluation phase.
I will also will make a lot of useful measurements on the way.

@vighneshbirodkar I will tell you the timing today.

I would attempt to import it at module scope, and then set a flag to indicate success.  E.g.:

```python
try:
    import pandas
except ImportError:
    _HAVE_PANDAS = False
else:
    _HAVE_PANDAS = True
```

I would then raise a ValueError inside `to_dataframe` if `_HAVE_PANDAS` is False.

Each of these if/return statements causes a double RPC call.  It would be better to write this as

```
try:
    return web3.eth.coinbase
except Whatever:
    pass

try:
    return web3.eth.accounts[0]
except Whatever:
    pass

return None
```

You could say:
```Python
return dcos_install_cli(client_version=client_version, install_location=install_location) if client_version else dcos_install_cli(install_location=install_location)
```

Also, I think if you created a kwargs dictionary, you could just say:

```Python
kwargs = {'install_location': install_location}
if client_version:
  kwargs['client_version'] = client_version
return dcos_install_cli(**kwargs)
```

Wouldn't it be better if we used for:

```python
for prefix in prefixes:
    if line.startswith(prefix)
        result[prefix] = child.pid
```

this flow is fine, maybe just DRY up with sth like 

```
def patch(self, url, data, **kwargs):
    if kwargs.get('files'):
        content_type = "multipart/form-data"
    else:
        content_type = "application/json"

    return self.request(
        "PATCH", url, content_type, data=json.dumps(data), **kwargs
    )
```
